  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating GIP Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The SGD 200M revenue threshold is strictly enforced. Unlike some countries where requirements are flexible, Singapore's EDB conducts thorough due diligence. If your company's audited financials show less than SGD 200M revenue, don't waste time on a GIP application—explore EntrePass or Employment Pass alternatives.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Treating EntrePass as an Easy Alternative</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">EntrePass has no minimum investment, but it's not easy. Your business must demonstrate genuine innovation—not just a viable business model. MOM rejects applications that are "me too" businesses without technological differentiation. VC backing, patents/IP, or incubator affiliation significantly strengthen applications.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Health Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Because insurance isn't mandatory for visa approval, some applicants delay arranging coverage. This is dangerous—a single hospitalization can cost SGD 50,000-200,000 at foreigner rates. Arrange comprehensive insurance before arriving in Singapore. The SGD 400-1,000/month premium is trivial compared to potential uninsured medical costs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring EntrePass Renewal Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">EntrePass renewals require demonstrating progress: hiring local employees, meeting minimum business spending (SGD 100,000+), and showing revenue growth. Founders who focus only on product development without local hiring often face renewal difficulties. Plan for these milestones from day one.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underbudgeting for Singapore Living Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Singapore is one of the world's most expensive cities. Family housing in good areas costs SGD 5,000-12,000/month; international schools cost SGD 30,000-50,000/year per child. Budget realistically—underfunded moves create stress that can undermine business success. Include domestic helper (common in Singapore) if you have young children.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Singapore -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Singapore</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Singapore has one of the world's best healthcare systems—ranked 6th globally by WHO. The system combines public hospitals (government-subsidized for citizens/PRs) with excellent private hospitals. For foreigners on work passes, private care is typically the better option since you pay full "foreigner" rates at public facilities anyway.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Public vs. Private Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Public Hospitals</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Singapore General Hospital (SGH)</li>
          <li>• National University Hospital (NUH)</li>
          <li>• Tan Tock Seng Hospital (TTSH)</li>
          <li>• Excellent quality—but long waits</li>
          <li>• Foreigner rates 3-5x citizen rates</li>
          <li>• Ward classes: A, B1, B2, C (C subsidized for citizens only)</li>
          <li>• Often used for complex procedures/emergencies</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Private Hospitals</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• Mount Elizabeth (Orchard & Novena)</li>
          <li>• Gleneagles Hospital</li>
          <li>• Raffles Hospital</li>
          <li>• Parkway East Hospital</li>
          <li>• Shorter waits, premium facilities</li>
          <li>• Higher costs (but covered by insurance)</li>
          <li>• Direct billing with most insurers</li>
          <li>• English widely spoken</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare for Different Residency Statuses</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">GIP Permanent Residents</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">As PRs, you gain access to subsidized healthcare rates (though less than citizens). You must contribute to CPF Medisave (8% of income) which can be used for approved medical expenses. Can purchase MediShield Life (national health insurance). Private insurance still recommended for comprehensive coverage and private hospital access.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">EntrePass / PEP Holders</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Work pass holders pay full foreigner rates at public hospitals—no subsidies. No CPF contributions or MediShield Life access. Private insurance is essential. Most employers provide some insurance; entrepreneurs must arrange their own coverage. Budget SGD 300-800/month for comprehensive plans.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Dependents (Spouse, Children)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dependent pass holders have same healthcare access as primary pass holder. Children can access pediatric care at both public and private hospitals. International schools often require proof of health insurance. Ensure your family plan covers pediatric and maternity (if relevant) comprehensively.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Medical tourism bonus:</strong> Singapore is a leading medical tourism destination—many come specifically for treatment. As a resident, you have easy access to world-class specialists in oncology, cardiology, orthopedics, and other fields. Private hospitals like Mount Elizabeth attract top physicians from around the world.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between GIP and EntrePass?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          GIP is for established business owners with proven track records (SGD 200M+ revenue, 3 years audited financials) who can invest SGD 10-50 million. It grants immediate permanent residence. EntrePass is for innovative startup founders—no minimum investment, but your business must demonstrate innovation and scalability. EntrePass gives a work pass initially, with a path to PR after 2+ years.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is health insurance mandatory for Singapore investor visas?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No—unlike European investor visas, Singapore does not require health insurance for visa approval. However, we strongly recommend comprehensive private insurance. Foreigners pay full "foreigner" rates at public hospitals (3-5x citizen rates), and a single hospitalization can cost SGD 50,000-200,000. Budget SGD 300-1,000/month for quality coverage.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family get PR through my GIP application?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. GIP allows you to include your spouse and unmarried children under 21 in your PR application. Parents can be sponsored separately after you obtain PR. Each family member needs their own health insurance. For EntrePass and PEP, family members receive Dependent Passes (not PR) and can apply for PR later based on your status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does it take to get Singapore citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You must first be a Permanent Resident for at least 2 years before applying for citizenship. Total timeline from GIP approval to citizenship eligibility is typically 2-4 years. Citizenship approval considers factors including: economic contribution, family ties to Singapore, integration into society, and national service obligations for male applicants/dependents.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my EntrePass renewal is rejected?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          EntrePass renewals require meeting milestones: hiring local employees, minimum business spending (SGD 100,000+), and demonstrating business progress. If you don't meet these benchmarks, MOM may reject renewal. You'd have 30 days to leave Singapore or appeal. To avoid this, plan for hiring and spending requirements from the start—they're not optional.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I maintain my GIP status while living outside Singapore?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          GIP PR comes with a Re-Entry Permit (REP) valid for 5 years. You must renew the REP to maintain PR status while traveling. Renewal requires demonstrating continued economic ties to Singapore—business operations, employment, investments. Extended absence without economic ties may result in REP non-renewal and loss of PR status. Plan to maintain substantive Singapore business presence.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Singapore's investor visa programs are designed for serious players—established business owners with proven track records (GIP) or innovative entrepreneurs building scalable ventures (EntrePass). The investment thresholds are high, but the rewards match: immediate permanent residence through GIP, 0% capital gains tax, 17% corporate tax, and access to Asia's premier business ecosystem.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For UHNW individuals seeking a base in Asia, the GIP's SGD 10-50 million investment threshold is substantial but delivers unmatched benefits: PR for the entire family, Singapore's world-class infrastructure, and a globally recognized business environment. The 2023 addition of Option C (Single Family Office) reflects Singapore's growing importance as a wealth management hub.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For startup founders, EntrePass offers a path to Singapore without massive capital—but your business must demonstrate genuine innovation. VC backing, strong IP, or incubator affiliation significantly strengthens applications. Plan for renewal requirements (local hiring, business spending) from day one.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Singapore investor visas suit serious investors and entrepreneurs who value tax efficiency, rule of law, and access to Asian markets. Health insurance isn't mandatory but is essential—budget SGD 400-1,000/month for comprehensive coverage. Work with specialized immigration advisors for GIP applications, and plan EntrePass milestones carefully. Singapore is expensive but delivers unmatched business advantages in Asia.
